					 SSH Configuration for GitHub and Azure DevOps


Step 1: Generate SSH Key for the User

 		ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "yourofficeemail.com"

Step 2: Copy the Public SSH Key to the Repository

		cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

Step 3: Create the SSH Configuration File
		
		touch ~/.ssh/config

Step 4: Add Configuration to the SSH Config File

# GitHub Configuration
		Host github.com
		  HostName github.com
		  User git
		  IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_rsa
		  IdentitiesOnly yes
		  StrictHostKeyChecking accept-new

# Azure DevOps Configuration

# Azure DevOps Configuration
		Host dev.azure.com
		  HostName <your_organization>.ssh.dev.azure.com
		  User git
		  IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_rsa
		  IdentitiesOnly yes
		  StrictHostKeyChecking accept-new

Step 5: Validate the SSH Configuration

For GitHub:
		ssh -T git@github.com

output:
	Hi username! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.


For Azure DevOps:
		ssh -T git@dev.azure.com

Step 6: Set Correct Permissions for SSH Keys
		
		chmod 700 ~/.ssh
		chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa
		chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

Step 7: Set Up Git for Pull and Push Operations

		git config --global user.email "yourofficeemail.com"
		git config --global user.name "Your Account Name"


Note: Changing from HTTPS to SSH URL

	If you've cloned a repository using HTTPS and want to switch to using SSH, run the following command in your repository directory:

	cd /path/to/repo
	# SSH URL: git@github.com:<owner>/<repo>.git
	git remote set-url origin git@github.com:<owner>/<repo>.git
